SECTION 1 — DEFINITIONS
================================================================================

1.1   "Frontend Application" or "Software" means the PlanIt client-side web
      application in its entirety, encompassing, without limitation:

      (a)  All React component source files (.jsx, .tsx) including but not
           limited to the Home, Admin, EventSpace, Discover, ReservePage,
           ClientPortal, WLHome, WhiteLabel signup, Status, Help, About,
           OrganizerLogin, TableService, GuestTablet, ServerView, Waitlist,
           LiveWaitBoard, EnterpriseCheckin, InviteBadge, InviteCard,
           GuestInvite, ReservationTicket, SecurityDashboard, Support, Terms,
           Privacy, NotFound, and all other page-level components;

      (b)  All context providers and consumer hooks including WhiteLabelContext,
           and any future context modules;

      (c)  All service modules, API client files, WebSocket client integrations,
           and utility functions located in the /src/services, /src/utils,
           /src/hooks, and related directories;

      (d)  All UI component library files, design tokens, Tailwind CSS
           configuration, custom CSS stylesheets, and animation definitions;

      (e)  The Vite build configuration, Vite plugin configurations, service
           worker registration logic, PWA manifest, and all build tooling
           configuration files;

      (f)  The public/ directory including index.html, robots.txt, sitemap.xml,
           PWA icons, og-image assets, and all other static assets shipped with
           the application;

      (g)  The complete visual design language of the application, including
           color palettes, typography choices, spacing systems, component
           interaction patterns, animation timing curves, gradient definitions,
           glassmorphism treatments, and the overall aesthetic system;

      (h)  The white-label theming architecture, including the CSS variable
           injection system, the [data-wl] attribute selector scheme, and the
           dynamic branding application logic;

      (i)  All documentation, code comments, inline explanations, and
           architectural decision records embedded in or accompanying the
           Frontend Application.

1.2   "Author" means Aakshat Hariharan, the sole designer, architect, developer,
      and intellectual property owner of the Frontend Application and every
      element thereof, including all visual design choices, component
      architectures, user experience flows, and implementation decisions.

1.3   "You" or "Licensee" means any natural person, developer, designer,
      engineer, researcher, student, company, organization, partnership,
      corporation, LLC, government body, educational institution, non-profit
      entity, or any other legal entity that in any manner accesses, views,
      reads, downloads, clones, forks, compiles, executes, deploys, screenshots,
      analyzes, reverse engineers, or otherwise interacts with the Frontend
      Application or any file, asset, component, or portion thereof.

1.4   "Hosted Service" means the publicly accessible production deployment of
      the PlanIt platform operated by the Author at planitapp.onrender.com and
      all associated subdomains and custom domains configured for white-label
      clients.

1.5   "White-Label Domain" means any custom domain configured by a paying
      white-label client of the Author that serves a customized instance of
      the Frontend Application under the client's own branding, pursuant to
      a separately executed white-label license agreement between the Author
      and that client.

1.6   "Visual Design System" means the complete set of design decisions embodied
      in the Frontend Application, including the dark color scheme (#080810,
      #0a0a0a base tones), the gradient language (blue-to-indigo primary
      gradients), the glassmorphism card treatments, the ambient radial glow
      background orbs, the typography hierarchy, the micro-interaction patterns,
      icon usage conventions, layout grid systems, and responsive breakpoint
      strategies — all of which constitute confidential trade dress and
      intellectual property of the Author.

1.7   "Derivative Work" means any software, website, web application, mobile
      application, design system, template, UI kit, component library, or other
      creative or functional work that: (a) incorporates, copies, or adapts any
      code, component, or design from the Frontend Application; (b) substantially
      replicates the look, feel, layout, interaction patterns, or user experience
      of the Frontend Application; (c) uses the Frontend Application's source
      code as a reference to build a competing or similar product; or (d) takes
      aesthetic inspiration from the Visual Design System in a way that would
      cause a reasonable person to identify a connection to the Frontend
      Application — regardless of whether any literal code was copied.

1.8   "Commercial Use" means any use of the Frontend Application, its design,
      components, or any Derivative Work thereof in connection with any revenue-
      generating activity, including SaaS products, consulting services, agency
      work, white-label resale, advertising-supported products, or any other
      commercially motivated deployment.

1.9   "Deploy" means to serve, host, publish, make publicly accessible, run in
      a browser context, or otherwise make operational the Frontend Application
      or any portion thereof on any infrastructure, including personal servers,
      cloud platforms, CDNs, GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, Render, AWS,
      Cloudflare Pages, or any other hosting environment.

1.10  "Distribute" means to share, transfer, publish, post, transmit, email,
      make available, sublicense, or otherwise disseminate the Frontend
      Application or any portion thereof to any third party through any channel,
      including but not limited to GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket, npm, package
      registries, file sharing services, cloud storage, or direct transfer.

